Sometimes audiences struggled to follow his dense arrangements - described by one group opposed to his modern style of music as "sonic sewage". In 1994, audiences at Covent Garden booed his opera Gawain, based on the medieval tale of Gawain And The Green Knight. While Last Night Of The Proms viewers struggled to understand his work Panic, and jammed the BBC switchboard with complaints. In Birtwistle's first opera, Punch And Judy, the female puppet met a violent death, shocking audience members at the Aldeburgh Festival in Suffolk in 1968. As the storms of controversy erupted, he kept quiet, telling one interviewer: "I don't know why there are problems. I don't understand what the problem is." Harrison Birtwistle was born in Accrington, Lancashire. His parents Fred and Madge ran a bakery but were not well off.